    <div class="help-header"><h2>PPI Calculator Guide</h2><p>Find your screen's true pixel density.</p></div>
    <div class="help-grid">
        <div class="help-card"><h3>The formula</h3><ul><li><strong>Diagonal pixels</strong> = √(width² + height²)</li><li><strong>PPI</strong> = diagonal pixels / diagonal inches</li><li>Dot pitch (mm) = 25.4 / PPI</li></ul></div>
        <div class="help-card"><h3>Common tiers</h3><ul><li>&lt;100 PPI: older TVs and large cheap monitors</li><li>100-150 PPI: typical 1080p / 1440p desktops</li><li>150-220 PPI: 4K monitors, premium laptops</li><li>220+ PPI: Retina / high-DPI (phones, MBP)</li></ul></div>
        <div class="help-card"><h3>Typical values</h3><ul><li>1080p 24": 92 PPI</li><li>1440p 27": 109 PPI</li><li>4K 27": 163 PPI</li><li>4K 32": 138 PPI</li><li>MBP 14" 3456×2234: 254 PPI</li></ul></div>
        <div class="help-card"><h3>Why it matters</h3><ul><li>Font rendering quality scales with PPI.</li><li>Display scaling (125%, 150%) is usually needed above 150 PPI.</li><li>Images made for print (300 DPI) look sharp on 300+ PPI screens without upscaling.</li></ul></div>
